{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_vrtx_01QdehQ3kWwRJLNCJTwZabmK","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"So the `namespaceSelector` from the CPPC is applied to the `MutatingWebhookConfiguration` itself — Kubernetes uses it to decide whether to invoke the webhook for pods in a given namespace. The webhook's `shouldIgnorePod` handles the hardcoded exclusions (`kube-*` prefix, operator namespace, DaemonSet, etc.).\n\nThe namespace `openshift-kube-apiserver` does NOT start with `kube-` — it starts with `openshift-`. So it wouldn't be caught by the `strings.HasPrefix(pod.Namespace, \"kube-\")` check. The only way it gets excluded is via the `namespaceSelector` on the webhook configuration.\n\nBut in the test setup, the `namespaceSelector` is NOT set on the MutatingWebhookConfiguration (see `getMutatingWebHook()` in suite_test.go — no `NamespaceSelector` field), meaning the webhook fires for all namespaces. The test suite creates a CPPC without a `namespaceSelector`, so all namespaces are included.\n\nWait — let me re-read the task: \"a pod created in the namespace `openshift-kube-apiserver` is NOT assigned the scheduling gate, even when ClusterPodPlacementConfig has a namespaceSelector that matches all namespaces.\"\n\nThis suggests the `openshift-kube-apiserver` namespace should be excluded by some mechanism. Let me look more carefully at the `shouldIgnorePod` and surrounding logic."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":375,"cache_read_input_tokens":61118,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":375,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"17f3279e-3ff4-4128-beca-9d4c7c1a551a","uuid":"8fc8b0b9-c0f0-4fe8-86a8-ee5abd609867","timestamp":"2026-07-20T17:22:12.001Z","request_id":"req_vrtx_011CdDhJ2QhCFCH7uWjd6H1T"}
