—they need explicit configuration via `namespaceSelector` on the ClusterPodPlacementConfig to prevent pods from getting gated. The test should verify that a pod with a control plane node selector in `openshift-kube-apiserver` doesn't get gated, and I need to make sure that namespace is created during the test setup.\n\nI can create the namespace within a BeforeEach block in my Context using the same `EnsureNamespaces` pattern that's already used in `seedK8S()`, then write the test to verify the pod placement behavior. I need to be careful about namespace creation since `EnsureNamespaces` uses `Create` which fails if the namespace already exists, but since this is an integration test with envtest, each run starts fresh so creating the namespace in the test itself should work fine. I'll follow the existing test patterns and make sure to verify that the pod doesn't have the scheduling gate or the gated label after creation. mutation happens synchronously during the `Create` call, so I can check the scheduling gates immediately after without needing to poll. I should verify that the gates aren't present on the pod to confirm the webhook correctly skipped the mutation.\n\nLooking at the imports, I notice the webhook test uses a regular import for the builder package while the reconciler test uses a dot import, so I need to make sure I'm using the right qualifier when calling `builder.NewPod()`.\n\nI also need to handle the namespace issue—`openshift-kube-apiserver` isn't created in the test setup, so I'll need to create it within the test itself, either in a `BeforeEach` or directly in the test block before creating the pod.\n\nBuilding the test pod with the container image and a generated name... The `namespaceSelector` in the MutatingWebhookConfiguration controls which namespaces the webhook fires for, so without one it applies to all namespaces—which is what the test needs to verify. I should check what imports are already available in the test file before adding anything new.\n\nI need to bring in the core Kubernetes types for Pod and Namespace objects, the meta types for object metadata, the operator's utility functions for the scheduling gate name and control plane label, and the controller-runtime client utilities for object key operations.\n\nAfter calling `k8sClient.Create`, the pod object should be updated in-place with the server-side response including any webhook mutations, so the scheduling gates should already be reflected. However, I should verify this by checking how the existing tests handle it — the webhook tests check the error immediately after Create since mutations happen synchronously during admission, while the reconciler tests use Eventually with Get since those modifications happen asynchronously. The webhook mutations add labels but not the scheduling gate, so I can verify the pod state directly after Create without needing a Get call. I'm leaning toward keeping it simple and following the existing webhook test pattern rather than adding extra robustness checks.\n\nFor the namespace setup, I should use `testingutils.EnsureNamespaces` to match the pattern already established in `seedK8S()` instead of manually creating a `corev1.Namespace` object.\n\nLooking at the exclusion logic in `shouldIgnorePod`, I need to verify which conditions apply to my test case. The pod shouldn't have the scheduling gate if it matches any of these: it's in the operator's namespace, in a kube-* namespace, already scheduled to a node, has a control plane node selector, or comes from a DaemonSet.\n\nBut here's the issue—`openshift-kube-apiserver` doesn't match the hardcoded exclusions in the code. The webhook configuration itself would need a `namespaceSelector` to exclude it, but in my test environment, there's no such selector, so the webhook would actually fire for all namespaces. This means I need to either add the namespace exclusion to the webhook config or ensure the test pod has one of the other exclusion properties. So the `openshift-*` namespaces aren't hardcoded as excluded—they only get excluded if the webhook's `namespaceSelector` is configured to skip them. Since the test has the webhook firing for all namespaces, the pod must be ignored through one of the `shouldIgnorePod` checks, and the most appropriate one for a kube-apiserver pod would be the control plane node selector check. I'll structure the test so the pod has that control plane node selector to verify it doesn't get gated.\n\nNow I need to check what `utils.Namespace()` returns in the test environment to understand how the namespace comparison works in the `shouldIgnorePod` logic.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":596,"cache_read_input_tokens":70214,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":596,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":12},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"17f3279e-3ff4-4128-beca-9d4c7c1a551a","uuid":"171478a1-5088-45ed-8bb0-1dfdabd82df4","timestamp":"2026-07-20T17:25:32.298Z","request_id":"req_vrtx_011CdDhSS8Bf1pb2zZ7FHs7N"}
