uld fail.\n\nI'm going to assume the pod needs a control plane node selector (like real kube-apiserver pods in OpenShift), and now I need to set up the imports for the test—I'll need the core API types for the scheduling gate and the utility functions for the gate name and node selector label. Each file needs its own imports, so I'll need to add the necessary ones to the webhook test file. I can either import the Kubernetes core and meta packages directly along with the utils package, or use the testing utilities helper and import that instead — both approaches would work, but I need to decide which keeps the code cleaner.\n\nActually, I'm realizing that `testingutils.EnsureNamespaces` already handles the namespace creation with error checking built in, so if I use that helper, I just need to make sure the namespace doesn't already exist from a previous test run. Since the suite setup only creates specific namespaces and this test would be adding a new one, it should be safe — though I should consider whether running the test multiple times in the same envtest instance could cause issues. The `EnsureNamespaces` function uses `Expect` assertions which work fine in any Ginkgo context, so I can call it from within an It block. Since the webhook and reconciler tests run in the same process, there shouldn't be issues with parallel execution. I'll keep it simple and just create the namespace inline in the test.\n\nNow I'm setting up a test case for handling a pod in the openshift-kube-apiserver namespace with a control plane node selector, creating that namespace first and then building a pod with specific container images from the registry. I need to add the remaining imports and then reconsider the test approach. The webhook runs synchronously during admission, so the pod object returned from `k8sClient.Create` should already have the mutations applied by the server. I could verify this directly on the pod object, though adding a Get call would be more defensive and consistent with how the reconciler tests are structured. add a `namespaceSelector` to the CPPC that explicitly matches all namespaces to make the test scenario clearer, since the webhook fires for all namespaces anyway. Now I'm ready to write the implementation and check what imports are needed.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":449,"cache_read_input_tokens":76704,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":449,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":8},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"17f3279e-3ff4-4128-beca-9d4c7c1a551a","uuid":"92bbe619-9930-4e8d-b863-66f03da99792","timestamp":"2026-07-20T17:26:45.444Z","request_id":"req_vrtx_011CdDhaQtVE7GvwN2R7Q63T"}
